(187,'Senator Gillibrand calls Trump Twitter post \'sexist smear\'','It also included New York Daily News and CNN reports with two other former pageant participants supporting Trump.','politicsNews','12-Dec-17','Senator Kirsten Gillibrand fired back at President Donald Trump on Tuesday and said she would not be silenced after he attacked her on Twitter for calling for an investigation into accusations of sexual harassment and misconduct against him. Trump, a Republican, has denied the allegations. Gowdy noted that congressional panels cannot prosecute crimes so he was forwarding the group’s letter to the Justice Department. More than a dozen women have accused Trump, a New York-based real estate developer and former reality television star, of making unwanted sexual advances against them years before he entered politics. Other Democratic lawmakers rallied behind Gillibrand, including U.S. Trump did not answer a reporter’s question at a White House event later on Tuesday when asked what he meant by the tweet. He added that any charges not alleging crimes should go to the House Judiciary Committee, which has jurisdiction over “allegations related to fitness for office and non-criminal matters.”   Trump has called the accusations fabricated stories and he has said he did not know his accusers.','Negative','-0.6705','Negative','-0.9231'),
(188,'Trump loses his big bet on Alabama U.S. Senate race','“He was trying to push a boulder up a hill,” Walsh said.','politicsNews','13-Dec-17','The victory by Democrat Doug Jones over the Republican Moore in the Alabama special election on Tuesday was a catastrophe for Trump, portending a Democratic wave next year that could cost Republicans control of one or both houses of Congress. But the combination of Trump’s unpopularity, the sexual misconduct allegations that erupted against Moore in November, and Trump’s enthusiastic support of him anyway gave them the opportunity, experts said. The stakes in Alabama were that high. “When you nominate candidates who are unqualified and an embarrassment to the party, you run the risk of ruining your entire brand,” said Josh Holmes, a Republican consultant and close ally of McConnell. ANTI-ESTABLISHMENT Beyond Moore, Bannon is supporting anti-establishment candidates such as Kelli Ward in Arizona, Danny Tarkanian in Nevada and Kevin Nicholson in Wisconsin, all of whom oppose McConnell staying on as Senate leader. Moore’s camp this week said the contest was specifically a referendum on Trump and his presidency. Democrats never expected to have a chance in Alabama, where they had not won a U.S. Senate race in 25 years.','Positive','0.3612','Positive','0.8622'),
