(209,'Trump\'s push to cut federal jobs has modest impact, mostly in defense','(This version of the story has been refiled to clarify description of the Partnership for Public Service in paragraph 15)','politicsNews','12-Dec-17','Days after his Jan. 20 inauguration, Trump ordered a hiring freeze later replaced with an order for federal agencies to cut staff immediately, and in March he proposed a 2018 budget that sought to shift $54 billion to the military from other departments. Mallory Barg Bulman, a researcher at the Partnership for Public Service, a non-partisan nonprofit, said targeting the number of jobs in general was not the best way of improving how the bureaucracy works. However, federal civilian jobs declined around 6,000 in the first nine months of this year, or just 0.3 percent of 2.1 million such jobs tracked by the Office of Personnel Management, according to Reuters calculations based on the latest OPM data published in late October. Instead, agencies should invest more in training to boost productivity, she said. Much of the gains were in divisions that control immigration and in medical care for former soldiers, areas Trump has identified as priorities. A spokeswoman at the Department of Homeland Security said staffing increases owed to revised recruitment strategies as well as temporary hiring for hurricane relief efforts.','Positive','0.93','Positive','0.9686'),
